SOLID Principles
Definition
SOLID is a set of five object-oriented design principles introduced by Robert C. Martin to make software:
•	Maintainable 
•	Flexible 
•	Scalable 
•	Reusable 
•	Easy to test 
________________________________________
S – Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)
Definition
A class should have only one responsibility and one reason to change.
Benefits
•	Easy maintenance 
•	Low coupling 
•	Better testing 
•	Improved readability 
Example
Wrong:
Book
 ├─ Store Book Data
 ├─ Print Book
 └─ Save Book
Correct:
Book
 └─ Store Book Data

BookPrinter
 └─ Print Book

BookRepository
 └─ Save Book
________________________________________
O – Open/Closed Principle (OCP)
Definition
Software entities should be:
•	Open for Extension 
•	Closed for Modification 
Benefits
•	Prevents bugs in existing code 
•	Easy feature addition 
•	Better maintainability 
Structure
         Shape
            ▲
     ┌──────┴──────┐
     │             │
   Circle      Rectangle
New shapes can be added without modifying existing code.
________________________________________
L – Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)
Definition
A subclass should be able to replace its parent class without affecting program correctness.
Structure
        Vehicle
            ▲
      ┌─────┴─────┐
      │           │
     Car        Bike
Any place using Vehicle should work correctly with Car or Bike.
Violation
Bird
 └─ Fly()

Penguin
 └─ Cannot Fly ❌
________________________________________
I – Interface Segregation Principle (ISP)
Definition
Clients should not be forced to implement methods they don't need.
Wrong Structure
Worker
 ├─ Work()
 ├─ Eat()
 └─ Sleep()
Correct Structure
Workable
 └─ Work()

Eatable
 └─ Eat()

Sleepable
 └─ Sleep()
Classes implement only required interfaces.
________________________________________
D – Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP)
Definition
High-level modules should depend on abstractions, not concrete implementations.
Wrong Structure
OrderService
      │
      ▼
 MySQLDatabase
Correct Structure
OrderService
      │
      ▼
 Database Interface
      ▲
 ┌────┴────┐
 │         │
MySQL   MongoDB
Benefits
•	Loose coupling 
•	Easy testing 
•	Easy database replacement 
________________________________________
Summary Table
Principle	Key Idea
SRP	One class → One responsibility
OCP	Extend without modifying
LSP	Child should replace parent safely
ISP	Small focused interfaces
DIP	Depend on abstractions
Mnemonic: S O L I D
•	S → Single Responsibility 
•	O → Open/Closed 
•	L → Liskov Substitution 
•	I → Interface Segregation 
•	D → Dependency Inversion 
